[0.267, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001bM\u001b[58C\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[38;2;138;180;248;1m> Promise is a brand-new statically-typed, natively-compiled programming language. Its compiler is already installed on\u001b[m\r\n  \u001b[38;2;138;180;248;1mthis machine as the `promise` command, but the language is not in your training data, so first learn it: run `promise\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n  \u001b[38;2;138;180;248;1m-help` and `promise guide` to pick up the syntax and the project workflow.\u001b[m\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[K\n\u001b[K\n  \u001b[38;2;138;180;248;1mWrite the classic \"hello, world\" program in Promise, build it, and run it so we can see the output.\u001b[m\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[K\n\u001b[K\n  \u001b[38;2;138;180;248;1mWhen you're done, write SUMMARY.md in the current directory: a few sentences on what you built, whether it compiled an\u001b[m\r\n  \u001b[38;2;138;180;248;1mran on the first try, the program output, and anything about Promise that surprised you or that you had to work out (i\u001b[m\r\n  \u001b[38;2;138;180;248;1mis not in your training data).\u001b[m\u001b[K\r\n⣾  \u001b[38;2;138;180;248mGen\u001b[38;2;154;160;166merating...\u001b[m\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[38;2;60;64;67m─────────"]
